<article>
    <h1>Na&#xAD;tional Gallery Sin&#xAD;ga&#xAD;pore</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>WHERE AD­MIS­SION</p>
    <p>1 St An­drew’s Road</p>
    <p>Free en­try to An Artist’s Trop­i­cal Land­scape; pre-book a slot at tick­ets.na­tion­al­gallery.sg/ac­tiv­i­ties or regis­ter for a slot at the venue.</p>
    <p>For Kep­pel Cen­tre for Art Ed­u­ca­tion, reg­is­tra­tion for a slot can be done at the venue en­trance</p>
    <p>INFO www.na­tion­al­gallery.sg</p>
    <p>THE LOW­DOWN</p>
    <p>The Na­tional Gallery Sin­ga­pore’s new of­fer­ings in­clude ac­tiv­i­ties for young chil­dren.</p>
    <p>An Artist’s Trop­i­cal Land­scape al­lows kids to ex­plore the world of trop­i­cal fruits through pi­o­neer Nanyang artist Ge­or­gette Chen’s paint­ings. The in­stal­la­tion is part of the mu­seum’s bi­en­nial chil­dren’s fes­ti­val Small Big Dream­ers.</p>
    <p>In a tie-up with Sin­ga­pore artist Yeo Shih Yun, the Kep­pel Cen­tre for Art Ed­u­ca­tion has two new ac­tiv­i­ties for chil­dren.</p>
    <p>In Art Playscape, they can cre­ate dig­i­tal art­works through in­stal­la­tions that sense mo­tion and sounds, while Ink Stu­dio lets them dis­cover un­usual tech­niques of ink paint­ing.</p>
    <p>FUN FAC­TOR</p>
    <p>Like many kids, my daugh­ters love mak­ing art and play­ing video games. So they are chuffed to be able to do both at Na­tional Gallery.</p>
    <p>In An Artist’s Trop­i­cal Land­scape, my seven-year-old gets to do a still-life draw­ing of trop­i­cal fruits.</p>
    <p>In the life-size Rambu­tan Room, she plays aug­mented re­al­ity games cen­tred on fruits, such as the pineap­ple.</p>
    <p>In Art Playscape, she gets to cre­ate dig­i­tal paint­ings through move­ments, giv­ing her an ex­cuse to run, scream and jump around.</p>
    <p>LEARN­ING VALUE</p>
    <p>My kids are ex­posed to how</p>
    <p>Chen re­lied on not just her eyes, but also all her other senses when creat­ing art.</p>
    <p>A lit­tle rudi­men­tary ro­bot mak­ing ran­dom brush­strokes in Ink Stu­dio also teaches kids that there are un­ex­pected ways to cre­ate art.</p>
    <p>ROOM FOR IM­PROVE­MENT</p>
    <p>My daugh­ter could only ob­serve and not han­dle the cute lit­tle ro­bots at Ink Stu­dio be­cause of safe man­age­ment mea­sures.</p>
    <p>INSIDER TIP</p>
    <p>At An Artist’s Trop­i­cal Land­scape, you can buy a kid’s activity pack with stick­ers and colour pen­cils for $5.</p>
    <p>WILL WE BE BACK?</p>
    <p>Def­i­nitely. The ac­tiv­i­ties were a fun way to en­gage the kids in art ap­pre­ci­a­tion un­der the guise of play.</p>

